🌪️ New Release Will Be Tuesday June 4th! 🚀 @subvortex ・7

🔧 Fixes and Enhancements:
Integration of the Andrew O Country API
Resync the metagraph as needed for miners
Fix Subtensor scripts
Adjust weights for the different scores

Upgrade details:

The new incentive mechanism weight scoring will be:

`Availability out of 8 - (40%)
Latency out of 7 - (35%)
Reliability out of 3 - (15%)
Distribution out of 2 - (10%)`

The new weights have reduced the Distribution scoring from 16.67% to 5%. This decreases the importance of having a miner in a unique country. We do not want good miners to be de-registered due to a new miner in their country (and still in immunity) hurting the good miners score just by being in the same country. By increasing the Latency, this should help steepen the curve as the latency scores miners against the other miners. This means miners will be de-registered based more on their performance vs their location. 

Coming soon:
We have been working on DDOs protection and hope to release an update for this soon. In the meantime, one of our valued community members @Austin  has provided some great scripts to help protect miners. We have not fully vetted this code ourselves as we have been building our own solution, so please do your own review and decide if you are comfortable using it. 

On the roadmap:
We are looking in to finding solutions so we can have miners run multiple subtensors on the same UID and be incentivized accordingly. This will create more variance in the distribution curve (theoretically could run 100+ subtensors and be at the top of the curve) and it will also mean there's no reason for miners to need more than 1 UID (more people can participate and reg costs would probably come down). We are speaking with Rhef who has successfully implemented a similar concept in his subnet. We still face the issue of needing a unique identifier from the subtensor itself to ensure that miner owns that subtensor.

The compute_latency_score function computes the latency score for a miner based on the process time and the geographical distance from the validator. Here's a step-by-step explanation of how it does this:

Check if the miner can be scored: The function first checks if the miner is eligible to have a latency score computed by calling can_compute_latency_score(miner). If the miner is not eligible (not verified or has IP conflicts), it returns a predefined penalty reward (LATENCY_FAILURE_REWARD).

Get the validator's location: It retrieves the geographical location (latitude and longitude) of the validator using the get_localisation function, which likely looks up the location based on the provided validator_country.

Compute process times with tolerance: The function iterates over all miners in the provided list and calculates a "tolerance" based on the geographical distance between each miner and the validator. This is done by:

Getting the miner's location.
Calculating the distance between the miner and the validator using compute_localisation_distance.
Scaling the distance by the maximum possible distance on Earth (MAX_DISTANCE) to get a scaled distance.
Calculating the tolerance as 1 - scaled_distance.
Adjusting the miner's process time by the tolerance to get a "process time with tolerance".
Baseline Latency Calculation: It calculates the baseline latency as the mean of all the adjusted process times.

Relative Latency Score Calculation: For each miner, it calculates a relative latency score as 1 - (process_time / baseline_latency). This gives a score that reflects how much better or worse each miner's latency is compared to the average.

Normalization: The function normalizes the relative latency scores by subtracting the minimum score from each score and then dividing by the range (max score - min score). This ensures that the scores are between 0 and 1.

Return the miner's score: It returns the normalized score for the specific miner being evaluated.

The latency score calculation takes into account both the raw process time and the geographical distance to the validator, which is a proxy for network latency. By adjusting the process time with a tolerance based on distance, miners that are geographically distant from the validator are not unfairly penalized for longer network latencies that are beyond their control.
